<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Previously only recorded from the Palaearctic region. A northern species, found in Norway, Sweden, and Finland, and across the northern Palaearctic to the Russian Far East and Japan (Hokkaido) (
<bibRefCitation author="Kazantsev, SV" editor="Loebl, I" journalOrPublisher="Zoologicheskii zhurnal" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" refId="B102" refString="Kazantsev, SV, Brancucci, M, Loebl, I, Smetana, A, 2007. Cantharidae. In: LoeblISmetanaA (Eds) Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera (Vol.4). Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 234-298." title="Cantharidae. In: LoeblISmetanaA (Eds) Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera (Vol. 4). Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 234 - 298." year="2007">Kazantsev and Brancucci 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Silfverberg, H" journalOrPublisher="Sahlbergia" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="1 - 144" refId="B188" refString="Silfverberg, H, 2010. Enumeratio renovata Coleopterorum Fennoscandiae, Daniae et Baltiae. Sahlbergia 16: 1 - 144" title="Enumeratio renovata Coleopterorum Fennoscandiae, Daniae et Baltiae." volume="16" year="2010">Silfverberg 2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rassi, P" journalOrPublisher="Sahlbergia" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="1 - 164" publicationUrl="http://www.luomus.fi/sites/default/files/sahlbergia/sahlbergia_21_S1_2015.pdf" refId="B171" refString="Rassi, P, Karjalainen, S, Clayhills, T, Helve, E, Hyvaerinen, E, Laurinharju, E, Malmberg, S, Mannerkoski, I, Martikainen, P, Mattila, J, Muona, J, Pentinsaari, M, Rutanen, I, Salokannel, J, Siitonen, J, Silfverberg, H, 2015. Kovakuoriaisten maakuntaluettelo 2015 [Provincial List of Finnish Coleoptera 2015]. Sahlbergia 21: 1 - 164" title="Kovakuoriaisten maakuntaluettelo 2015 [Provincial List of Finnish Coleoptera 2015]." url="http://www.luomus.fi/sites/default/files/sahlbergia/sahlbergia_21_S1_2015.pdf" volume="21" year="2015">Rassi et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Probably Holarctic and previously overlooked in North America.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="canadian records">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Canadian records.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Yukon Territory: Ivvavik National Park, 17-Jun-2014 to 23-Jun-2014 (3 exx CBG); Ivvavik National Park, 23-Jun-2014 to 29-Jun-2014 (16 exx, CBG).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="diagnostic information">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Diagnostic information</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
(based on 
<bibRefCitation author="Kazantsev, SV" journalOrPublisher="Zoologicheskii zhurnal" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="572 - 575" refId="B101" refString="Kazantsev, SV, 1998. Novye rossiiskie vidy Dichelotarsus (Coleoptera, Cantharidae) [New Russian species of Dichelotarsus (Coleoptera, Cantharidae)]. Zoologicheskii zhurnal 77: 572 - 575" title="Novye rossiiskie vidy Dichelotarsus (Coleoptera, Cantharidae) [New Russian species of Dichelotarsus (Coleoptera, Cantharidae)]." volume="77" year="1998">Kazantsev 1998</bibRefCitation>
). Body length 7-10 mm. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 27, 28" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figures 27, 28. 27 Dichelotarsus lapponicus (Gyllenhal) 27 A habitus 27 B aedeagus, ventral view (everted endophallus removed) 27 C aedeagus, lateral view (everted endophallus removed) 27 D endophallus, lateral view 28 Malthodes pumilus (Brebisson), habitus, L. Borowiec. Scale bars: 2.0 mm (27 A), 0.5 mm (27 B-D), 0.3 mm (28)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures27-28" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362150" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures27-28">Fig. 27A</figureCitation>
. Dark brown to black, basal antennomeres, mandibles and usually clypeus (at least at the margins) yellow. Legs variably yellow, usually at least the profemora yellow. Third antennomere in males ca. 1.5 times as long as the second. Pronotum as wide as long or slightly wider than long, with sides concave before acute hind angles. All tarsal claws in both sexes with a broad, blunt basal tooth, no claws deeply cleft. Aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 27, 28" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figures 27, 28. 27 Dichelotarsus lapponicus (Gyllenhal) 27 A habitus 27 B aedeagus, ventral view (everted endophallus removed) 27 C aedeagus, lateral view (everted endophallus removed) 27 D endophallus, lateral view 28 Malthodes pumilus (Brebisson), habitus, L. Borowiec. Scale bars: 2.0 mm (27 A), 0.5 mm (27 B-D), 0.3 mm (28)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures27-28" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362150" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures27-28">Fig. 27B−D</figureCitation>
, with dorsal plate with apical notch.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="bionomic notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Bionomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">In Northern Finland, this species is found both above and below the treeline, usually in wetlands (MP, pers. obs.). The Canadian specimens were collected with a Malaise trap on tundra close to the Arctic treeline.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
The remote arctic collecting locality suggests that this species is more likely to be Holarctic than adventive from the Palaearctic region. The legs and basal antennomeres of the Canadian specimens are darker and the body length is slightly smaller compared to North European material we examined (including the DNA barcoded Finnish specimens with which the Canadian specimens share the BIN cluster). The male genitalia and shape of the pronotum show no differences between the European and Canadian specimens. Based on the identification keys, descriptions and figures by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fall, HC" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Americana" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="65 - 103" refId="B61" refString="Fall, HC, 1927. A review of the North American species of Podabrus. Entomologica Americana 8: 65 - 103" title="A review of the North American species of Podabrus." volume="8" year="1927">Fall (1927)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Fender, KM" editor="Hatch, MH" journalOrPublisher="The American Midland Naturalist" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" refId="B63" refString="Fender, KM, Hatch, MH, 1961. Family Cantharidae. In: HatchMH (Ed.) Beetles of the Pacific Northwest.Part III: Pselaphidae and Diversicornia I. University of Washington Press, Seattle, 44-68." title="Family Cantharidae. In: HatchMH (Ed.) Beetles of the Pacific Northwest. Part III: Pselaphidae and Diversicornia I. University of Washington Press, Seattle, 44 - 68." year="1961">Fender (1961)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. lapponicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="lapponicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. lapponicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
closely resembles 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. piniphilus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="piniphilus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. piniphilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Eschscholtz, 1830). The tarsal claw formula is the same and the shape of the pronotum is very similar in both species. The dorsal plate of the aedeagus has an apical notch in 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. lapponicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="lapponicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. lapponicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 27, 28" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figures 27, 28. 27 Dichelotarsus lapponicus (Gyllenhal) 27 A habitus 27 B aedeagus, ventral view (everted endophallus removed) 27 C aedeagus, lateral view (everted endophallus removed) 27 D endophallus, lateral view 28 Malthodes pumilus (Brebisson), habitus, L. Borowiec. Scale bars: 2.0 mm (27 A), 0.5 mm (27 B-D), 0.3 mm (28)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures27-28" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362150" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figures27-28">Fig. 27B</figureCitation>
), whereas in 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. piniphilus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="piniphilus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. piniphilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is apically truncate or subtruncate. The clypeus of 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. lapponicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="lapponicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. lapponicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is usually yellow at least at the margins. The yellow color is more extensive in males in the material we have seen, and only faint red-brown spots are visible on the clypeus of some female specimens. The clypeus is black in 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. piniphilus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="piniphilus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. piniphilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3752/cjai.2014.25" author="Pelletier, GA" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Arthropod Identification" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="1 - 246" refId="B167" refString="Pelletier, GA, Hebert, C, 2014. The Cantharidae of Eastern Canada and Northeastern United States. Canadian Journal of Arthropod Identification 25: 1 - 246" title="The Cantharidae of Eastern Canada and Northeastern United States." url="https://doi.org/10.3752/cjai.2014.25" volume="25" year="2014">
Pelletier and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hébert">Hebert</normalizedToken>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
state that 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. lapponicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="lapponicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. lapponicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. perplexus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="perplexus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. perplexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(W.J. Brown, 1940), which is known from across boreal and arctic Canada, but 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. perplexus" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="perplexus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">D. perplexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is smaller (body length 5.0-6.5 mm) and has a different tarsal claw formula.
</paragraph>
